.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:3:DESIGN.md follows the [official Google Stitch DESIGN.md format](https://stitch.withgoogle.com/docs/design-md/format/): YAML frontmatter carrying machine-readable design tokens, followed by a markdown body with exactly six sections in a fixed order. **Tokens are normative; prose provides context for how to apply them.** Sections may be omitted when not relevant, but **do not reorder them and do not rename them**. Section headers must match the spec character-for-character so the file stays parseable by other DESIGN.md-aware tools (Stitch itself, awesome-design-md, skill-rest, etc.).
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:5:## The frontmatter: token schema
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:7:The YAML frontmatter is the machine-readable layer. It's what Stitch's linter validates and what the live panel renders tiles from. Keep it tight; every entry should correspond to a token the project actually uses.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:45:- **Token refs** use `{path.to.token}` (e.g. `{colors.primary}`, `{rounded.md}`). Components may reference primitives; primitives may not reference each other.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:47:- **Component sub-tokens** are limited to 8 props: `backgroundColor`, `textColor`, `typography`, `rounded`, `padding`, `size`, `height`, `width`. Shadows, motion, focus rings, backdrop-filter — none of those fit. Carry them in the sidecar (Step 4b).
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:73:- **Scan mode** (default): the project has design tokens, components, or rendered output. Extract, then confirm descriptive language. Use when there's code to analyze.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:76:Decide by scanning first (Scan mode Step 1). If the scan finds no tokens, no component files, and no rendered site, offer seed mode — don't silently switch. `$impeccable document --seed` forces seed mode regardless of code presence.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:86:3. **CSS-in-JS theme files** — styled-components, emotion, vanilla-extract, stitches: look for `theme.ts`, `tokens.ts`, or equivalent.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:87:4. **Design token files** — `tokens.json`, `design-tokens.json`, Style Dictionary output, W3C token community group format.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:90:7. **Visible rendered output** — if browser automation tools are available, load the live site and sample computed styles from key elements (body, h1, a, button, .card). This catches values that tokens miss.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:94:Build a structured draft from the discovered tokens. For each token class:
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:104:From the auto-extracted tokens, draft the YAML frontmatter now (you'll write it at the top of DESIGN.md in Step 4). This is the machine-readable layer — what the live panel and Stitch's linter consume.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:106:- **Colors**: one entry per extracted color. Key = descriptive slug (`warm-ash-cream`, `editorial-magenta`, not `blue-800`). Value = whichever format the project treats as canonical (OKLCH or hex — see the frontmatter rules above). Don't split the source of truth: one format in the frontmatter, don't redefine the same token in prose with a different value.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:111:Skip anything the project doesn't have. Empty scale keys or fabricated tokens pollute the spec.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:242:The frontmatter owns token primitives (colors, typography, rounded, spacing, components). The sidecar at `DESIGN.json` carries **what Stitch's schema can't hold**: tonal ramps per color, shadow/elevation tokens, motion tokens, breakpoints, full component HTML/CSS snippets (the panel renders these into a shadow DOM), and narrative (north star, rules, do's/don'ts). It extends the frontmatter, it doesn't duplicate it.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:292:**What changed from schemaVersion 1.** The old sidecar carried token primitive arrays (`tokens.colors[]`, `tokens.typography[]`, etc.). Those values now live in the frontmatter. The sidecar only carries metadata that can't live in the frontmatter — tonal ramps, canonical OKLCH when the hex is an approximation, display names, role hints — keyed by the frontmatter token name (`colorMeta.<token-name>`, `typographyMeta.<token-name>`). Components still carry full HTML/CSS because Stitch's 8-prop set can't hold them.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:299:2. **Token resolution.** If the project exposes tokens as CSS custom properties on `:root` (e.g. `--color-primary`, `--radius-md`), reference them via `var(--color-primary)` — they inherit through the shadow DOM and stay live-bound. If tokens live only in JS theme objects (styled-components, CSS-in-JS), resolve to literal values at generation time.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:313:If the project has **no component library yet** (bare landing page, new project), synthesize canonical primitives from the tokens using best-practice defaults consistent with the DESIGN.md's rules. Every DESIGN.json has *something* to render, even on day zero.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:317:For each color token, generate an 8-step `tonalRamp` array — dark to light, same hue and chroma, stepped lightness from ~15% to ~95%. The panel renders this as a strip under the swatch. If the project already defines a tonal scale (Material `surface-container-low` family, Tailwind-style `blue-50..blue-900`), use those values. Otherwise synthesize in OKLCH.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:344:Before interviewing: "There's no existing visual system to scan. I'll ask five quick questions to seed a starter DESIGN.md. You can re-run `$impeccable document` once there's code, to capture the real tokens and components. OK?"
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:383:<!-- SEED — re-run $impeccable document once there's code to capture the actual tokens and components. -->
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:395:Seed mode writes a minimal frontmatter with `name` and `description` only — no colors, typography, rounded, spacing, or components yet. Real tokens land on the next Scan-mode run. Skip the `DESIGN.json` sidecar in seed mode for the same reason: nothing to render.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:400:2. Tell the user: "Re-run `$impeccable document` once you have some code. That pass will extract real tokens and generate the sidecar."
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:405:- **Frontmatter first, prose second.** Tokens go in the YAML frontmatter; prose contextualizes them. Don't redefine a token value in two places — the frontmatter is normative.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:409:- **Functional > decorative**: for each token, explain WHERE and WHY it's used, not just WHAT it is.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:420:- Don't extract every token. Stop at what's actually reused — one-offs pollute the system.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:426:- Don't duplicate token values between frontmatter and prose. If a color is in `colors.primary` as hex, the prose can name it and describe its role but should not reassert a different hex. The frontmatter is normative.
.\agent\docs\codex-harness-engineering\templates\package-assets\skills\impeccable\reference\document.md:427:- Don't invent frontmatter token groups outside Stitch's schema (no `motion:`, `breakpoints:`, `shadows:` at the top level). Stitch's Zod schema only accepts `colors`, `typography`, `rounded`, `spacing`, `components`. Anything else belongs in the sidecar's `extensions`.
